Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph concerning the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
At second reading, MEPs rejected the proposed amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the door to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for entering into an a priori disadvantaged agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the convicted woman in December.
Tymosenko describes the regime's political revenge judgment and has provoked a process of suspicion of bias of the court also to the west.
The draft repeal of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
