Feeding an obese child: do not take breakfast and take meat for dinner
Over a third of children aged 9-13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important is the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is found 50% more often than in normal-weight children's families.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of the big kids sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and 900 pupils from primary schools in Chechnya participated.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight and even obese children is the absence of proper nutrition and insufficient physical exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned indicate, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast-in-case - lunch-tasting-dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and cold cuts at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students' families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been noted is that one tenth of the population doesn't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is, however, the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in obese children's families, unhealthy fries are more often consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sports regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Get your food ready.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet based on options offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of a healthy diet."
Among their favorite dishes there are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is in particular a high preference for sweet lemonades", is indicated in the results of the survey.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
Children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health heading
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet," the results of the survey indicate.
For example, the most notable was sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and knedliky (Czech speciality of breadmeal or potato pellets).
