How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a western inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to queue up all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The journeys of the Czechs have been a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 holidays in Eastern Germany and Bulgaria were at most, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holiday days in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbours led to a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip from Czechs was at that time to take with it its own preserved food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased what has caused another important moment around 1997.
With increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 begun to prepare tours with air charter connections which, thanks to contracts, have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 90s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the US that later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
From this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries each year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history, and for the first time in history they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for a holiday abroad, including the associated expenses. Crowns per person.
