Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that strengthens your heart.
A hint to start with: carefully tear this page apart and make it your brand.
You will learn to know these people in detail. In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments where, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the haze of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which issues the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book that he accurately describes as "an anti-history book."
It has some well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; almost no ambassadors or discussions on strategies and materials are found.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." It contains the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulances and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose their limbs, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives vacillate here like the candles of a church: while some are dying, new ones are being lit up.
Peter Englund's book deviates from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that the First World War is only summed up by the terrible trench war on the western front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; a Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks the cordite.
When the cannon blows in the distance, and you are a mother in the home, do you stay or run away?
Who's going to come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been exacerbated by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most approach deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz. "
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 authorized substitute meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories address honor and courage.
