How to detect a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how much deception and lies are omnipresent in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The Penn State administrators were accused of perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open microphone stating to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
Congressman Anthony Weiner of New York and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner went for an idiot by quickly emitting denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with violations of the funding of campaigns related to the coverage of an extramarital relationship.
And then, none of the people who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton set up when he lied during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave the test answers to students in order to get a good look at their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are godly lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detection or detection of lies is an essential competence that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to cry out: "I had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research of such projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about the lie have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don't stutter, blush, or get agitated all the time.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are able to read well others, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "centered on them" while women tell more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "setting the benchmark data."
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring future changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally shakes his feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him shaking his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and nonverbal misleading behaviors.
Consider these clues red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use distanced language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... if I remember correctly... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
