Climate adversity has slowed the economy
In the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has declined and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-called of change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing losses of billions for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction in economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic 31.16 per cent decline in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the gelatin allocation report from the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were 582 million 835 hectares of crop damage, 78.03 per cent of which suffered total damage and the rest 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, while the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the State until November, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three quarters of the year has been observed an accelerated increase, because during January to March 55 thousand 053 Signoons were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average has continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Signoons unemployed, an increase from the first half of 18 thousand 969 persons.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and use them in something," he says.
Migration in detention
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to work abroad in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they enter the state they already have a lot of difficulties in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which means that unemployment is rising," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Danish labour market is aggravated by the high level of lack of seriousness which predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state work there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's shift is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly earnings of the workers in Denmark were, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment over the past 10 years, according to the Economy Secretariat from January to June, the State's FDI reached $630 thousand,697, a decrease of 87.74 per cent from the $5,143,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, registered mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, in July the Government of the State requested the approval of a 3 trillion peso credit for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 trillion peso, and until November no debt benefits were observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the will of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The return on Sinaloa's economy this year was really very poor, we have to work hard to get back the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have to align the effort of everyone and above all the already synchronised good work of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year have retained the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is produced by several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Patrons of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he says.
A lot to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that better channels the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that a lot of work has been done and the Government is aware of the fact that there is still a lot to do," he says.
