Debts towards contributions to works
Social works included in programmes such as Habitat, Rescue of Public Spaces and 3x1 paramigrants may not be completed where there are serious delays due to lack of economic resources, reported Miguel Ángel López Miranda.
The Director of Municipal Social Development said that although construction programmes have progressed so far, they are at risk because the Government of the State has not fulfilled its obligations to provide contributions that exceed 11 million pesos in all three programmes.
He noted that in total, the investment of these three programmes is approximately 50 million pesos, of which the State must provide 25 per cent and so far only the Federation and the Municipality have provided resources for the works, therefore there is the possibility of a delay in their finalization.
"They have to make a contribution of 12 million and despite the fact that the year will soon end they have given us nothing, even if since July they had to give us a part of it," he says, "and we, in order not to record delays, have started the works and we have made a lot of progress, but we need money".
He mentioned that last year, during the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla, the state had not paid the corresponding contributions, therefore at the beginning of the administration the municipality had to apply for a credit to cover the 7 million that the state administration had not provided on that occasion.
"We had already experienced this in the previous six-year period because the state had not had the economic capacity to participate and the programs continue to work and this year we, in order to have access to these programs, had to obtain the resources to cover what the state had not paid for," he said.
Despite the fact that there was a commitment on the part of the State authorities to provide these resources, he stated that they had requested the Secretary of Administration and Finance, Armando Villarreal, to activate management so that the corresponding percentages would arrive as soon as possible.
"They have to provide almost 12 million and despite the fact that the year is coming to an end, they have given us nothing."
The Court validates "analogue cut" in Mexico in 2015
Substitution of analog signals with digital is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue coupure" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is a statutory assignment to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favour of the draft voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also decided to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his intervention, the Minister-President said that he disagreed with the project's arguments, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure measures through general standards for the public administration to prepare for them.
"I do not consider that this would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has as its constitutional mandate the management of the State.
Substitution of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this results in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitisation, which implies a decision of public interest that does not only have a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "requires the operation of an entire system to establish, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the State Executive".
He recalled that many countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has in a form invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislature, he asserts.
Analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data shown by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of the "vote-by-vote" count is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data evidenced by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second places of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve his Political Constitution or Electoral Code of State or Electoral Justice Act, while the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period for this electoral process to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel failed to publish it within the time limits provided for in the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9th November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislature and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms, because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to realize the partial and total counts of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of the vote and there is no record of the vote in the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to be the winner of the election and the candidate who obtained the second place in the election is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition who submitted the second of the nominated candidates.
The total count of the ballot may also be made if at the end of the common count it follows that the difference between the candidate presumed to be the winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party whose candidate has emerged second, in which case electoral packages which have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
