The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the entire Eurozone at risk.
A communiqué from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
He is expected to present a majority cabinet composed of technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the outcome of his conversations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well mapped out," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels that cannot be sustained.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough package of austerity demanded by the European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of markets has placed the yield of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland have had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said that we would support this government a lot".
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added itself to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.9 trillion, would be too much for the current financial defenses of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give it time to implement reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreement between parties complicates the attempt to include political figures.
