Quinteto has included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament, from Pearl Jam, said the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday on the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to occur in this country.
It is that bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is on the South American wing of its two-decade work tour and Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
That day they will present themselves on the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 pm, next to the Los Angeles group The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the complete transcript of which is found in La Nación on the Internet.
For Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I only spent in Costa Rica once the holidays; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we're excited to wear our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the group, fans live intensely in the days before.
What is your message for your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us for all these years.
It took 21 years for us to arrive in Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to go through this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add some pressure to your visit.
Some of the biggest shows we've offered over the last 21 years have been held in the last two weeks.
We have offered Sao Paolo a huge two shows and we hope that this has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of surfers friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned, through the people who love surfing.
When you saw the tour, you had offered huge shows, with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we never happened there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to play two songs of each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is the reason for this?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone loves different songs, which is why it's very difficult to choose which songs to play each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we love these songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together gives us a lot of emotion.
We love each other and love to create music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to form part of this group of large groups.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
This is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw in Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them again and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It is also very strange that a group like yours remains united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
