So it was the work of the person of Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A typewriter from Cali came to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano'.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4, a CTI typewriter from Cali passed to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a harvester and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
Looking for the fingerprint
For a typewriter from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Typyloscopying is an accurate science, without any margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying the bodies, the typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search the database.
The researcher said that in a case of theft he had to remove part of a wall from a house, because in that place the thief had held his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint from all hands and identify the offender who had participated in various thefts," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also remove or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of booze around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a parent may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him at the crime scene.
A CTI typist explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents are extracted".
When they appear, a harvester or a band is used to harvest them.
Later, fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is how it is shown in the CSI television program.
As all that shines is not gold, everything that is touched does not necessarily become a footprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indignant" defies the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were buzzing in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large part of the population accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement defied the New York authorities this Tuesday by trying to re-enter, thanks to a court order, the place of Manhattan, where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park of the Great Apple.
Hundreds of protesters were shaking in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a court order that allowed the 'indignant' to camp again in that place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
"Our idea is that if the court doesn't allow us to camp again in the square, we will move to another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," says one of the spokespersons of the Occupy Wall Street movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the "indignant" response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, reached the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the site and allowing protesters to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignant' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved as a sign of support to the members of the movement and tried to intervene in their favor before the police.
Meanwhile, the Zuccotti Square - which is a private property enclosure - remains closed pending the holding of a judicial hearing scheduled for this Tuesday during which we must analyse the legality of this morning's evacuation.
Some protesters who had been displaced until then were carrying and distributing copies of this court order at that time, and they were even handing it over to the officers who were monitoring the place, which caused 'some small clashes', said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials hit the protesters.
The judicial order prohibits the authorities from evacuating Occupy Wall Street members or applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or from denying demonstrators access to the park again with tents or other properties they used to use'.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, because of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and demonstrators, but warned that local laws did not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn at Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the demonstrators 'violate the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to hurt other people", because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
Officials of Occupy Wall Street also indicated that they do not plan to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on 17 September.
