Japan resurrects after the earthquake
GDP increases by 1.5% due to domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral in early March
Since March the Japanese economy has been paralysed, convalescent even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the Japanese country since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government have calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global environment, seems to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page definitively: GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualised rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also implies the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the aftermath of the tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of continuous increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refugee values" elected by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the expected turmoil of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic flotation line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, were responsible for their low performance between July and September for the Yen's contribution.
While the markets continue to sit in the peripheral EU countries, Yoshihiko Noda's Government does not decrease its guard.
"We must follow the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
Indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
Because it dropped four decimals to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in level 100, falling by eight decimals to 99.13 points.
Athens re-energizes doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitment
With the peripheral risk premiums triggered and the uncertainty re-installed in the parks, Greece continues to entangle itself in the maze that leads to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek Transitional Government is being imposed rather by the Brussels demands than by a real conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos pointed out yesterday that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the 100-day period set in his appointment may be short to apply, the leader of the Conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the scheduled date, that of 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the 26 October summit," Papadimos said when he opened a parliamentary debate yesterday that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to stimulate employment, reform of the civil servants' disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not cast doubt on his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the Transitional Government, but we have committed ourselves to nothing more".
The conservative leader has gone a step further in his pulse than the EU and IMF, the bodies that must unlock the 8,000 million that Athens urgently requires, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to implement the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the va-t-tout of the referendum in Papandreu, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
The spokesman for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the Troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new Government "the elements necessary to pay the sixth instalment" of 8,000 million, even if there is no final date either.
The Greeks still have a lot to do.
Queen Sofia: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen underlines Spain's "preponderant" role in this type of finance
Spain "has reached a world-leading place in the role of Microfinance".
Queen Sofia recalled that in the last two decades the country has become the world's second largest donor in terms of this instrument of cooperation, the essence of which lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
Yesterday, the Queen inaugurated the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that these types of operations are "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Development Goals set by the United Nations for 2015, and, "very specifically, in the one that aims to halve the volume of people living on incomes below one dollar a day, to which is set the "poverty threshold".
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in all corners of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofia, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions originating during the Summit, which will extend until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved many goals" and "we face many challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is seen not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to drive "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that at the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families are emerging from the poverty line in which they now live.
The impulse in the design of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, emphasized Queen Sofia as an "act of justice and recognition due".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", the work she has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to learn about her loan policy on the ground.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those held in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "at each meeting I was able to see a continuous evolution", explained Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought yesterday the term "head of the family" gathered in Valladolid by the "banking of the poor".
Finally, Queen Sofia ended her intervention by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in seeking solutions to progress in the fight against poverty.
"Ethic imperative"
The Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In this sense, she stated that it would be a mistake to link cooperation with developing countries to times of economic prosperity, because it is a "permanent obligation".
Jiménez considered that microcredits presuppose "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work on criteria of solidarity and not let it be the victim of the cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "trust" to "excluded persons to whom all close the door"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed people present in a city that "opens its contaminated doors of the spirit of solidarity".
CDU proposes to elect the European President by universal suffrage
The first day of the Congress of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), Monday 14 November, in Leipzig, took place without real difficulty for Angela Merkel, Chancellor but also President of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not originally foreseen in the programme but was imposed in the autumn, in particular to satisfy the activists who consider the government's policy too lax with regard to the Greeks today and perhaps Italians tomorrow.
The motion on the Presidency of the European Commission, proposed by management, was adopted almost unanimously.
Of the 1001 delegates, only nine voted against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes to which they were entitled, after their interventions, Angela Merkel then, a few hours later, Wolfgang Schäuble, the very Europhile Minister of Finance, left no room for doubt.
The master idea of the Chancellor - and of the motion - stands in a slogan: the answer to the crisis "is no less of Europe but more of Europe".
Not only because Europe is peace, but because "nine million jobs depend directly on the euro".
For the Chancellor, "the time has come from a breakthrough in Europe".
This could result in amendments to the Lisbon Treaty to strengthen the EU's control over the fiscal policies of the euro area countries, but it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage "in order to give Europe a face".
This is in any case one of the motion's proposals adopted by the Congress whose inspiration is clearly Wolfgang Schäuble.
Of course, it is unlikely that the Twenty-Seven will agree quickly on this revolution: Britain is hostile to it and the CDU leaders believe that Nicolas Sarkozy is also hostile.
But the milestone is set.
