In an effort to calm the climate within her party, the Chancellor multiplied the references to Konrad Adenauer and Helmut Kohl, but she also did not seek to win her congress on the back of the "small" European countries or countries in difficulty that were quick to criticize the arrogant Germany.
While the motion on Europe devotes a paragraph to the importance of "French-German friendship", Angela Merkel did not mention France.
Except in the hollow.
Remembering that two centuries ago, Leipzig had been at the heart of a bloody battle.
In fact, it was one of the most humiliating defeats of the Napoleonic army.
What does fraud at sick stops mean?
After the allowances, the UMP and the government launch the strike on the disease stops.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a family allowance fund, and to deliver a speech on the recurring theme - since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and assistance.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less heralding an axis of the presidential campaign to the right, the majority wants to focus on the sick stops.
Firstly, with a view to budgetary savings: the government plans to impose on private employees a fourth day of deficiency before taking over a work stoppage.
Clearly, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' wages, so at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could provoke anger, but would bring back 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic in scope: to impose on civil servants a day of non-compensation in the event of a stoppage of work (they do not have until now a period of absence, compared to three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also revives the issue of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, in addition, if you are caught, you will refund," Xavier Bertrand warned RTL's microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the advertising effects appear to be somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
Since 2002, it has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us first look at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Health Economics Research and Documentation, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, with EUR 11.3 billion.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, or €6.2 billion.
And therefore 2.5% of health expenditure.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 days in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides some discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the Monster.com career management site, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees interviewed said they had not taken any sick leave.
Another study, this time of the Health Insurance , specifies that in 2010, 37% of the sickness breaks were of a duration of less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more inclined than elsewhere to stop working.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) in France ranged from 10% to 11%, compared to 20% to 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sickness fraud represents very little in the face of work in the dark.
As for fraud, it is only of a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that controls are systematic on sick leave for more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million controls, CNAM found that 13 per cent of 285 000 cases for short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of systematically controlled arrests of more than 45 days, there were 11% "unadapted or unwarranted" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132,000.
A total of 169,000 "unwarranted" cases, out of several million employees who have had a sick leave.
A figure that represents very little compared, for example, to that of black work.
According to MP UMP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than the fraud against them.
Papadémos: Greece will have to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to restore its economy.
That is what the Prime Minister, Lucas Papadémos, told Parliament on Monday 14 November, adding that the one hundred days given to his union government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"To continue efforts to restore the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new fiscal adjustment programme," said the head of government, who was delivering his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, as the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake", he added.
As a result, Mr Papadémos has forecast that the country's public deficit will be reduced to "about 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after being 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
