Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described as "extreme" the position of the experts who signed the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to patients in the terminal phase.
"It opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask for help in committing suicide," says Mr. Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
But "in society, he says, there are beacons and constraints."
Health Law Specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "a strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she described as "pro-euthanasia demonstration".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, particularly challenges the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, in the Netherlands and Oregon.
