The government of Austria's major ruling social-democratic/Christian coalition decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budgetary "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid any deterioration by the rating agencies of the sovereign note of Austria (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, whereas the Austrian public debt was 74.6%, well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
