Energy policy:
the facts must prevail over the dogmas
If it is a subject that cannot be dealt with on short-term or emotional grounds, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is good that an election meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place nuclear power holds in them.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be addressed in order to continue to generate electricity on an ongoing basis, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
It is not the case either of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a substitute source capable of replacing itself, nor of Switzerland, which just intends to build only last generation power stations.
Conversely, the Czech Republic, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park by restarting the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts speech.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, in particular from Russia, a rise in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
He is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to wind intermittence, from which he draws 30% of his electricity; according to which his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are 65% and 50% higher, respectively, than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than those of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a pledge to maintain the industrial tool in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power illusory.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show any opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show this.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has built an industrial sector of 125,000 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly exportative, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very job-creating non-localizable.
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, it would be to sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the annual €6 billion in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would command an EPR designed to run sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a security authority that exercises intransigent and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville yard.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same safety obsession.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and the unforgivable human faults caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident resulted from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it had for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the security authorities, the operators and the French and German manufacturers, the EPR presents a concept that makes it able to resist such phenomena.
