More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that was the subject of the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23rd) proclaiming in the passage that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right on this subject.
To the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and to the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't accept all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared to the left as well as to the right.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps paid electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting anemia immigration growth and harming employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants may replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, by putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes to national employees, mostly in occupations in sectors with a shortage of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow job supply.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenues less expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to public budgets on average throughout his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to go and look for the missing growth points "with teeth".
The teeth in question, by being used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought of
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient, for democracy to triumph definitively with its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know from Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, the Lights, economic and social solidarity, a justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first of all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true Greek referendum will have had the value of double revealing: that of the necessity of a powerful return of politics, but also of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and that, for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in scattered order.
A whitewash to the absolute European monarch or a leap on foot attached in the void of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cutbacks, but a common, full-fledged, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we cannot stop the list anymore - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the diktats of markets and rating agencies, which suffer from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
For it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without total democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long fight against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for the European economic government.
That's it.
But thinking about it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must assume a new stage in European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more democratic Europe politically, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let's make Europeans.
