North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests including four heads of state and government participated, last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, to the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1224 km tube connecting the Saint Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site looks like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will in fact allow the delivery of gas directly to Germany, avoiding any overland passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years Russia has been able to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are declining.
" This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically, " confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic large gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
" A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the number of measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up off their coasts.
" In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute, " says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline is leaked into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the pipeline condition is carried out by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
Of the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one metre in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 metres per second, he delivers accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo any repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars from the start, and 100 bars from the finish line.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who holds 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have established a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to Gazprom for twenty renewable years.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity regardless of the amount of gas actually transported, " says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to be EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give back the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white colour, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design notes but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (tupe skin), which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
" Moleskine has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century " , says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook of notes attracts both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, now has almost 100 employees and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in bookstores, from the Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a wide range of media.
A success that made envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Disturbing?
" No, " notes Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
" The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable. "
" At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. "
" Nevertheless, much remains to be done. "
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before they enter employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, these are criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work, and that are "the node of the problem", according to Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for objective restraints.
It remains the unsaid, the mentality that is evolving, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually deficient".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, dating back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
" We are now around 3%, " says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies, " explains Pierre Blanc. "
" But this improvement also reflects real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
